> When one thread stalls, say, because it is waiting for data to arrive from memory, the CPU can execute instructions from the other thread.
What youâ€™re describing is temporal multithreading. However, hyperthreading is an implementation of Simultaneous Multithreading (SMT), in which instructions from both threads can be dispatched and executed at the same time.





